<p>
  During the 2014 Scottish Referendum part of the desire for change was based around creating a fair and equal society for everyone by narrowing the gap between the richest and poorest. Based on this, and my background in healthcare, I decided to do a bit of investigation into how the general health of Scots differs from the most well off to the least. To be fair, I was expecting there to be a difference but the size of the gap was actually quite surprising as you will see below.
</p>
<p>
  Now, rather than boring you with a lot of tables and dry statistics I decided to put some of my recent work on data visualisation into practice to try and present the information in a more visually interesting way.
</p>
<p>
  I tried to find the most up to date census data that was openly published and to begin with I looked at the good health rate from the Scotland Census 2011 which I managed to pull from the <a title="Office of National Statistics" href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/datasets-and-tables/index.html" target="_blank">Office of National Statistics</a>. The good health rate is the proportion of residents in each parliamentary constituency who reported themselves as having 'Very Good' or 'Good' general health as a percentage of the total of all residents in each constituency.
</p>
