<p>
  Premature mortality essentially means that a person has died before the age of their life expectancy and there is a huge gap here and the same goes for all cause mortality for the younger sector of the population. It's a surprising and sad situation that in a well developed country such as Scotland there can still exist such differences in health between the most well off and the least.
</p>
<p>
  Looking at the other figures it strikes me that a factor in the differences we saw from the above charts could be due to lifestyle choices, in particular diet &amp; exercise (play a large role in coronary heart disease), smoking (trachea/bronchus/lung cancer are quite highly attributable to smoking but not the only causes) and alcohol as these are where the absolute ranges are the greatest. Now, how to tackle this is beyond the scope of this article but there is much better information available today for the public to make more informed choices as well as government schemes to reduce the availability and advertising for cigarettes and raising the price of cigarettes and alcohol. I want to see if things like better information and advancements in healthcare have worked to make everyone healthier in comparison to previous years and also to see if the gap between the most and least deprived has changed much over the years.
</p>
