<p>
  Hope you found that useful! First up, there's good news in that premature mortality is showing a downward trend for both most and least deprived. It's difficult to know exactly why without further analysis but I'm sure advancements in medical treatments have helped. Also positive is that the absolute range has narrowed in the last 4 years of the data. Also of note is deaths from coronary heart disease with a downward trend and a narrowing gap. Given the initial scale of the problem, reducing these figures has probably had a reasonable effect on the downward trend of premature mortality.
</p>
<p>
  Sadly, for the other data sets the lines are fairly flat and even though in some cases, such as trachea/broncus/lung cancer and alcohol admissions, the gap has narrowed from 1998 to 2011 there are a lot of fluctuations in the figures so it isn't really following a trend yet. More data will be needed to see how this compares in future years.
</p>
<p>
What is clear is that there has existed a gap in the health of the most and least deprived for many years which needs attention in order to narrow it. Hopefully data for more recent years will shed some light on the current picture and I hope for positive results. If not then new ways need to be found to tackle the problems because such health divides in an advanced country should not exist.
</p>